Let’s break it down clearly.

🧠 Option 1: Common Database (Monolith + Microservices)
✅ When it is OK (your current stage)

👉 For learning / transition phase, it’s perfectly fine

✔️ Why it’s okay now:
Easy to manage ✅
No duplication of data ✅
Faster development ✅
Helps you understand microservices step-by-step

👉 In your case:

You already have monolith working
You’re slowly building microservices

👉 So shared DB is a practical starting point

❌ Why it’s NOT recommended long-term

This is where real architecture comes in 👇

🚨 Problem 1: Tight Coupling

If both services use same DB:

User table change → breaks multiple services ❌

👉 Microservices should be independent

🚨 Problem 2: No Ownership

In microservices:

👉 Each service should own its data

Example:

User Service → User DB
Content Service → Content DB

👉 Shared DB breaks this principle

🚨 Problem 3: Deployment issues

👉 If DB schema changes:

You must coordinate all services ❌
No independent deployment ❌
🚨 Problem 4: Scalability limitations

👉 You can’t scale services independently if DB is shared

🧠 Option 2: Separate Database (Recommended)
✅ Why this is best (real-world)

Each microservice:

User Service → user_db
Content Service → content_db
✔️ Benefits:
Independent deployment ✅
Loose coupling ✅
Better scalability ✅
Real microservices architecture ✅
